Reference for 9front hget(1), hpost(1), webpaste(1), urlencode(1): HTTP retrieval and posting via webfs(4); all flags; form scraping; URL encoding.

# 9front hget(1) — retrieve or post to a URL

## Synopsis

    hget [-l | -o file] [-e file] [-p body | -P] [-r header] [-m method] [-b baseurl] url
    hpost [-l] [-g action | -p action | -m action] [-r header] [-u] url [name:value | name@file] ...
    webpaste [file]
    urlencode [-d] [file]

## Description

`hget`, `hpost`, `webpaste`, and `urlencode` are rc(1) scripts (except
`urlencode`, which is a compiled C program) for working with HTTP from the
Plan 9 command line.  They all require `webfs(4)` to be running and mounted
at `/mnt/web`.

### hget

`hget` fetches the resource at `url` and writes its body to stdout.

**Flags:**

    -l           Print the Location URL from the response instead of
                 the body.  Useful after a POST that redirects to a
                 result URL (avoids re-fetching uploaded data).

    -o file      Keep file in sync with the remote URL.  If the remote
                 has been modified more recently than file, overwrite it.
                 If file exists but is incomplete, fetch only the missing
                 bytes (Range: request).

    -e file      Write the server's error response body to file instead
                 of discarding it (by default error bodies are ignored).

    -p body      POST the string body to the URL (performs HTTP POST
                 instead of GET).

    -P           POST data read from stdin (instead of a string argument).

    -r header    Add an arbitrary HTTP request header.  May be repeated
                 for multiple headers.  Example: `-r 'Authorization: Bearer tok'`.

    -m method    Override the HTTP method (default GET, or POST when -p/-P
                 is given).  Example: `-m DELETE`.

    -b baseurl   Interpret url as relative to baseurl.

**How it works:** hget opens `/mnt/web/clone`, reads a connection number,
then writes the URL (and optional baseurl, headers, POST body, method) to
the connection's `ctl` file via the webfs(4) interface.  The response body
is read from `body`; content-encoding is handled automatically
(`gzip` → gunzip, `bzip2` → bunzip2, `compress` → uncompress).

### hpost

`hpost` has two operating modes:

**Form scraping mode** (no `-g`/`-p`/`-m` given): fetches `url`, parses
its HTML forms, and prints rc(1) commands to stdout that would submit those
forms with their default field values.  The user can then edit and run the
printed commands.

**Form submission mode** (with `-g`, `-p`, or `-m`): fetches `url`, parses
its forms, then immediately invokes `hget` to submit the form to `action`.

**Flags:**

    -l              Pass -l to hget (print Location instead of body).

    -u              Treat the next argument as the target URL when it does
                    not immediately follow the last option.  Usually omitted.

    -r header       Pass an extra HTTP header to hget.

    -g action       Set form method to GET; use action as the relative
                    form action URL.

    -p action       Set form method to POST (url-encoded body); use action
                    as the relative form action URL.

    -m action       Set form method to POST with Content-Type
                    multipart/form-data; use action as the relative form
                    action URL.  Required for file uploads; files must be
                    seekable (file(1) is invoked to determine MIME type).

**Field arguments** (after the URL):

    name:value      Provide a text field value; overrides the form's default.
    name@file       Provide a file for a file-upload field.

### webpaste

`webpaste` uploads content to `http://okturing.com` and prints the URL where
it can be retrieved.  Input is stdin if no file argument is given.

    ns | webpaste            # paste output of ns(1)
    webpaste /tmp/notes.txt  # paste a file

### urlencode

`urlencode` percent-encodes or decodes data according to RFC 3986 rules.
Reads from file (or stdin if no file is given); writes to stdout.

    urlencode file      # encode
    urlencode -d file   # decode

Characters left unencoded: letters, digits, and `/ $ - _ @ . ! * ' ( ) ,`.
Spaces are encoded as `+`.  All other bytes are encoded as `%XX`.

## webfs(4) connection model

`hget` is built directly on top of webfs(4).  Understanding the model helps
when scripting HTTP directly:

1. Open `/mnt/web/clone` for reading to get a connection number `n`.
2. The clone file is now equivalent to `/mnt/web/n/ctl`.
3. Write configuration to `/mnt/web/n/ctl`:
   - `url URL`
   - `baseurl URL`
   - `headers Header-Line`
   - `request METHOD` (default GET; writing to postbody implies POST)
4. Write POST body to `/mnt/web/n/postbody` if needed (this initiates the
   request and must complete before body is opened).
5. Open `/mnt/web/n/body` to initiate the request and stream the response.
6. Read response metadata from `/mnt/web/n/contenttype`,
   `/mnt/web/n/contentlength`, `/mnt/web/n/contentencoding`,
   `/mnt/web/n/contentrange`, `/mnt/web/n/parsed/url`, etc.
7. On error, open `/mnt/web/n/errorbody` for the server's error payload.

## Examples

Download a file:
    hget http://9front.org/img/nix-on.jpg > /tmp/nix-on.jpg

Fetch and unpack a tarball (content-encoding handled automatically):
    hget http://example.com/src.tar.gz | tar xzf -

POST data:
    hget -p 'q=plan9' http://example.com/search

POST from stdin:
    echo 'some data' | hget -P http://example.com/upload

HEAD request only:
    hget -m HEAD http://example.com/

Send a custom header:
    hget -r 'Accept: application/json' http://api.example.com/data

Relative URL from a base:
    hget -b http://example.com/subdir/ ../other/page.html

Sync a local file with a remote URL (only fetch if newer):
    hget -o /tmp/index.html http://example.com/

Retrieve the Location after a POST redirect:
    hget -l -p 'data=x' http://example.com/submit

Scrape a form and view the submission command:
    hpost http://p.intma.in

Submit a form directly:
    hpost -u http://p.intma.in -p paste.cgi text:'test post'

Upload a file and print the resulting URL:
    hpost -l http://i.intma.in file@/tmp/screen.png | rc

Upload the output of ns(1) to a pastebin:
    ns | webpaste

URL encode a string (using a temporary file or pipe via hget scripting):
    echo 'hello world' | urlencode

URL decode:
    echo 'hello+world%21' | urlencode -d

## Diagnostics

`hget`, `hpost`, and `webpaste` require `webfs(4)` to be running and
mounted at `/mnt/web`.  If it is not, they will fail with an error opening
`/mnt/web/clone`.

To start webfs manually:
    webfs

